Correlation 1

Exercise 1 -

Use the cor.test() function to run a correlation. Select any two numeric variables of interest for your correlation. Interpret the output in terms of significance and direction.

cor.test(billboard$spotify_track_duration_ms,
         billboard$spotify_track_popularity)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  billboard$spotify_track_duration_ms and billboard$spotify_track_popularity
## t = 10.871, df = 4147, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.1367243 0.1958990
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.1664615

INTERPRETATION: There is a small, significant (p < 0.05) positive correlation between track popularity and track duration. (ANSWER WILL DEPEND ON VARIABLES CHOSEN).

Exercise 2 -

Create a ggplot scatterplot visualization of the two variables you selected for the correlation. Add a geom_smooth regression âlmâ line to the plot. Interpret what you see. Make sure you clean up the labels and add a theme.

ggplot(billboard, aes(spotify_track_duration_ms,
                  spotify_track_popularity)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_minimal() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  labs(x = "Song Length (ms)", y = "Song Popularity")

INTERPRETAION: While it is positive, we see most of the song length clustering is around 250000 ms. (ANSWER WILL DEPEND ON VARIABLES CHOSEN).

Below I am creating a new dataset called state_nurses that we will use only in this exercise and exercise 8. Fill in and replace âSTATE ONEâ and âSTATE TWOâ with the two states you selected.

Exercise 10 - Nurse Hourly Wage t-test

Now you run your t-test. Your goal is to test if there is a significant difference in Hourly Wage Avg based on the states (State) you selected. Note: You will have to write the variable name Hourly Wage Avg in the code below within back-ticks â`â because the variable name contains spaces.

t.test(`Hourly Wage Avg` ~ State, data = state_nurses)

Exercise 12 - Graphing Nurse Hourly Wage

Below I have created a basic ggplot code chunk to observe the differences. Your task is to improve the graph by: Cleaning up all of the labels, adding a title, make each bar a different color, and add a theme. See https://ggplot2-book.org/polishing.html for a list of included themes. Finally, interpret what you see.

ggplot(state_nurses, aes(State, `Hourly Wage Avg`, fill = State)) +

  guides(fill = "none") +

Exercise 19: Renaming Columns

We want to rename all of the columns! Change species to Species, island to Island, bill_length_mm to Bill Length (mm), bill_depth_mm to Bill Depth (mm), flipper_length_mm to Flipper Length (mm), body_mass_g to Body Mass (g), sex to Sex, year to Year. You must start your code with: penguins_renamed <- penguins %>% in order to save these changes to a new dataset called penguins_renamed. You will use the rename() function to accomplish this.

penguins_renamed <- penguins %>%
  rename(
    Species = `species`,
    Island = `island`,
    `Bill Length (mm)` = `bill_length_mm`,
    `Bill Depth (mm)` = `bill_depth_mm`,
    `Flipper Length (mm)` = `flipper_length_mm`,
    `Body Mass (g)` = `body_mass_g`,
    `Sex` = `sex`,
    `Year` = `year`
  )

Exercise 20: Calculating Frequenies

Now, using the new penguins_renamed dataset do the following:

  • group_by Sex, and then

  • filter with the argument !is.na(Sex) inside of the filter parentheses. This will remove penguins with no recorded sex from showing up.

  • Use summarize to calculate the percentage of penguins. group_by will do this separately for male versus female penguins automatically. Inside of the parentheses, first add a label for the name of this new column. For example, you could name it Percent. Then, add an = and fill in an equation that will calculate the percentage. You will use this format: n()/nrow(CODEHERE)*100. Where it says CODEHERE put in the name of the dataset we are working with. This formula will take the n() of each group (how many males versus females in the dataset), divide it by the total sample size with nrow(), and multiply it by 100 to get the percentage with *100.

penguins_renamed %>%
  group_by(Sex) %>%
  filter(!is.na(Sex)) %>%
  summarize(Percent = n()/nrow(penguins_renamed)*100) 
## # A tibble: 2 Ã 2
##   Sex    Percent
##   <fct>    <dbl>
## 1 female    48.0
## 2 male      48.8

Exercise 21: Recoding Levels

For this exercise we want to recode the levels of the Sex variable. Run the levels command below.

levels(as.factor(penguins_renamed$Sex))
## [1] "female" "male"

As you can see, the levels start with a lowercase letter. In the code chunk below, use mutate and case_when to change male to Male and female to Female. Hint: there is an example of case_when() in the lecture video on recoding data. Start your code with penguins_renamed <- penguins_renamed %>% to update these changes to the penguins_renamed dataset.

penguins_renamed <- penguins_renamed %>%
  mutate(Sex = case_when(
    Sex == "male" ~ "Male",
    Sex == "female" ~ "Female",
  ))

Exercise 22: Graphing

Finally, we want to customize a graph. Below I have created an initial template for you. Running this code will return a blank canvas of a graph. In order to complete the graph, add the following to the graph:

  • inside of the first aes(), add on a fill = Sex argument inside of the parenthesis. Make sure to use a , after Species when adding this code.

  • add on + geom_col() to create a graph with columns. Inside of the parentheses, add position = "fill".

  • add on + scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "BLANK") to change the colors of the graph. I have put a placeholder of "BLANK" for now. Replace this with one of the following: "mako", "magma", "plasma", "inferno", "cividis", "rocket", or "turbo". These all represent different color options. Play around and pick the one you like best.

  • and on a theme with theme_BLANK(). Replace the blank with one of the following: minimal, bw, classic, dark, get, grey, gray, light, linedraw, replace, test, or update.

  • finally, add on + theme() with legend.position = "bottom" set as the option inside of the parentheses.

ggplot(penguins_renamed %>% filter(!is.na(Sex)), aes(x = `Body Mass (g)`, y = Species, fill = Sex)) +
  geom_col(position = "fill") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "turbo") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position =  "bottom")
